link: Alois P. Heinz, Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000
Index entries for sequences related to sums of squares
formula: a(n) = [x^n y^9] Product_{k>=1} 1/(1 - y*x^(k^2)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 19 2019

a(n) = Sum_{q=1..floor(n/9)} Sum_{p=q..floor((n-q)/8)} Sum_{o=p..floor((n-p-q)/6)} Sum_{m=o..floor((n-o-p-q)/6)} Sum_{l=m..floor((n-m-o-p-q)/5)} Sum_{k=l..floor((n-l-m-o-p-q)/4)} Sum_{j=k..floor((n-k-l-m-o-p-q)/3)} Sum_{i=j..floor((n-j-k-l-m-o-p-q)/2)} A010052(i) * A010052(j) * A010052(k) * A010052(l) * A010052(m) * A010052(o) * A010052(p) * A010052(q) * A010052(n-i-j-k-l-m-o-p-q). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Apr 19 2019
